ements of objects they made in their ritual places--and how these forms and patterns in turn shaped their experience. How Ancient Europeans Saw the World offers a completely new approach to the study of Bronze Age and Iron Age Europe, and represents a major challenge to existing views about prehistoric cultures. The book demonstrates why we cannot interpret the structures that Europe's pre-Roman inhabitants built in the landscape, the ways they arranged their settlements and burial sites, or the complex patterning of their art on the basis of what these things look like to us. Rather, we must view these objects and visual patterns as they were meant to be seen by the ancient peoples who fashioned them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAntiquities, PrehistoriczEurope, Western. 0aBronze agezEurope, Western. 0aHISTORYvAncientvGeneral. 0aHISTORYzEuropevGeneral. 0aIron agezEurope, Western. 0aMaterial culturezEurope, Western. 0aPrehistoric peopleszEurope, Western. 0aSymbolism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aBronze Age.  aCeltic objects.  aEarly Bronze Age.  aGermanic style.  aIron Age.  aLate Iron Age.  aMediterranean world.  aMiddle Ages.  aMiddle Iron Age.  aRoman conquest.  aRome.  aactions.  aartifacts.  abowls.  aburial chambers.  aclothing pins.  acoinage.  acoins.  acups.  afibulae.  afocus.  aframe.  agraves.  ahouses.  aimagery.  aintegration.  ajars.  alandscape.  alate prehistoric Europe.  alight.  amaterial culture.  ametal ornaments.  aobjects.  aoptical process.  aornament.  aperformance.  aphysiological process.  apottery.  apre-Roman Europe.  aprehistoric community.  aprehistoric culture.  aritual.  asafety pins.  ascabbard.  asettlement.  asettlements.  asocial contact.  asocial 